"Yes, Captain. They should be on their way by now; they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations." Exactly at 0500, the Exodus Company gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are being relocated to the forward deployment base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos," Shaw explained. "Our mission is to support the ongoing siege and the subsequent attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There, we will establish a base at the foot of the mountains." "March to your squads and mount up."
The company disbanded into its respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed among the tanks by the sergeants. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further ahead in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days earlier, but knew little about them. He sat sideways, swinging his legs, while he adjusted his backpack and the radio set, which was connected to his headphones and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" Nemic asked after they had settled in.
"Are you talking about the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they let the animal go from a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small rooster, who was constantly turning his head to scan the surroundings.
"Yes, he's still with him," answered Cohren as the hatch of the tank opened and the commander came into view.
"All tanks are moving out," the commander spoke slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the column of tanks and Strykers roared as they got underway. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding in, shook as the brakes were released and they integrated into the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania Plain. Despite the winter storms having frozen the swamp areas and snowed the forests, the mud was still omnipresent.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whose name Cohren knew was Orson, began to speak. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the war began, right?"
"Yes, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought the matter would be settled in a few weeks, but we underestimated them."
"Underestimating them is a strong understatement," Nemic interjected. "We were not prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the sheer number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly by the side of the Federation," said Orson defiantly. "I will not let these terrorists intimidate me."
"That's what you say now," explained Craith. "But I've seen that most eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot."
"We'll see about that," said Cohren, laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We're picking up heat signatures, about 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed up onto the tank and put on his special glasses. When he switched them to "thermal imaging" mode, he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," answered Cohren over his larynx microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't recognize them," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said, "Exodus Company, fire only when under fire. Lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like heat signatures took shape. When they came even closer, one of them hurried off to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground; they took up firing positions.
"We have enemy contact!" Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracers were fired from the hillside. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket zoomed past and struck behind the formation, hitting the ground, exploding, and scattering debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another rocket hit the side of a Stryker, an APS Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition went up in flames.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees to the right, 300 meters. Fire at will," shouted the commander of the tank platoon over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire; grenades flew toward the hillside and exploded, throwing dirt and rock into the air.
"Send the Sentis in," Knoxx called, observing the hill with binoculars. The rear door of a Cerberus opened, and an unarmed soldier emerged, wearing a special headset. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis—officially called Sentinels—rushed out. Swinging their thin, metallic arms and legs forward, they launched into a sprint. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" asked Craith, as they watched.
"It looks like a capture," Cohren suspected as the two Sentinels disappeared into the cloud of ash and smoke. Shouts and gunshots echoed from the hillside, but soon fell silent. Shortly afterwards, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them whose boots left tracks in the ground. After they had taken cover behind the train, they threw the figure to the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the figure that was just trying to stand up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," replied the Sentinel. "The rest fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
